“We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join them with our foreheads up, not at the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If we are not wanted by the name of Macedonia, we can go to other countries, such as China and Russia, and we can become part of the Eurasian Union.”
Prime Minister Zaev said joining NATO would bring much-needed investments to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
“I think the majority will be in favour of changing the name, because more than 80% of our citizens are in favour of joining NATO and the EU,” Zaev said after voting.
He said an outcome in favor of the name change would be “confirmation of our future.”
