Throughout Bolivia, which has no way out to sea, the memory of a coast lost to Chile in a bloody 19th-century resource conflict is still alive – just as the desire to sail back into the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are probably at the highest level in decades as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court of Justice on October 1, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the necessary momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, awaits the outcome with a positive vision,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the ICJ’s decision on big screens across the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of Bolivia’s claim and that after decades of firm talks, Chile is forced to negotiate a sovereign exit to the sea, Bolivia.
