North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that extending sanctions would deepen mistrust in the United States and that it is impossible for its country to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the Global Council that North Korea had implemented “significant measures to prove its good faith” last year, such as stopping nuclear tests and missile testing, dismantling the nuclear test site and committing to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see any appropriate response from the United States," he said.
“If we can’t trust the United States, we won’t trust our national security capabilities, and under such circumstances, we can’t unilaterally disarm first.”
While Ri repeated North Korea’s familiar objections to Washington’s resistance to a “staggered” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded if it took step by step, his statement seemed significant because it did not directly reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at a first-ever summit between an incumbent U.S. president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to make progress toward a “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump offered assurances on North Korea’s security.
North Korea sought an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington has not responded to calls to ease harsh international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on the ‘denuclearization first’ option and increases the pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive way, even objecting to the ‘declaration of end of war’,” Ri said.
“The impression that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion that only people who don’t know us have.
But the problem is that prolonged sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader referred to at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae-in, the president of South Korea, over the past five months, adding: "If the issue of denuclearization had been negotiated with South Korea and not with the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse."
Even in these circumstances, the tone of Ri’s speech was very different from last year’s speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target U.S. territory with missiles from North Korea after “the evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea with “total destruction,” praised Kim for his courage to start the disarmament process, but said work was just beginning and sanctions would remain in place until North Korea is denuclearized.
