Harvard Students Take Courses on How to Get Enough Rest
A new course at Harvard University this year encourages students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the growing “macho” culture that makes them undergo “all-night” learning sessions, energized with a lot of caffeine.
One scientist found that students at the world’s most prestigious university often don’t even master the basic concepts of how they should take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the one who created the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a lecture on the impact of lack of sleep on the ability to learn.
“At the end, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I being told this just now, in the last year?’
She told me she had never been told about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, introduced for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance, as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students were seriously sleep deprived during the week.
An hour-long course can involve a number of interactive tasks.
In a section, the image of a dorm room is presented, and students can click on coffee mugs, curtains, sports pants and books to tell them what the effects of caffeine and light are and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deficiency, but also about the importance of a sleep schedule.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily schedule.
“We know we can’t instantly change the behavior of students.
But we believe that they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” Czeisler said.
The culture that makes students proud that they learned all night still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure on students have turned sleep deprivation into a growing problem.
Sufficient sleep of good quality should be a student’s “secret weapon” for combating stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, even to avoid weight gain because sleep deprivation makes the brain think that the body is starving, which makes students feel that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemical biology and physics, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after attending one of his first year courses at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for all students.
The next step, he hopes, is to require all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before enrolling at this institution where competition is fierce.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set an alarm to know when it is time to go to bed, as well as for waking time, and to know what are the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LEDs, which can disturb the circadian rhythm and cause difficulties when they try to fall asleep.
