National Trust spies on bats' secret lives
New research that is being conducted on a property in the Scottish Highlands wants to reveal how bats use the environment to hunt their prey.
It is hoped that the findings will reveal new things about the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help future conservation activities.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will look at common dwarf bats and pygmy bats, as well as ear bats and water bats from the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using manual detectors.
Specialized audio analysis of all recordings will estimate the frequency of sounds made by bats and what species emit certain sounds.
A habitat map and a report will also be produced to create a detailed, scaled-up picture of their behaviour in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grass creation, and what is the best way to maintain forest pastures for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably in the last century.
They are endangered by the construction and development work that affects their nests, as well as the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and street lighting are also risks, as are flies traps and some chemical treatments for building materials, as well as attacks from domestic cats.
Actually, bats aren't blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, is thinking very seriously about bats.
They have ten trained experts, who periodically conduct studies, control nests, and sometimes conduct rescue missions.
The organization even created the first and only bat reserve in Scotland, on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight out of ten species of bat in Scotland are found.
The manager of the estate, David Thompson, says this is the ideal territory for bats.
“Here at Threave, the area is great for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there's a lot we don't know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand what they need to multiply."
It stresses the importance of looking for bats before performing property maintenance work, as the mere unintentional destruction of a maternal nest could kill up to 400 females and young, which can destroy the entire local population.
Bats are protected, and killing, harassing or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests, are prohibited actions.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help them.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about bats, and we don't know how populations evolve for many of our species."
