She continued: “I received significant help from a woman in an executive position who told me that she was also crying when she was nervous, but that she developed a technique whereby, when she got angry and started crying, she would say to the person she was talking to, ‘You might think I’m sad, because you see me crying.
I'm nervous."
And then it goes on.
I thought it was a brilliant thing.”
Tears are allowed for the exteriorization of anger, partly because they are fundamentally misunderstood.
One of the clearest memories from one of my first jobs, in a male-dominated office, where I started crying because of an inexpressible anger, is that I was grabbed by the neck by an older woman, a cold director I always felt a little afraid of, and she took me down the staircase.
“They should never see you cry,” she said.
“They don’t know you’re angry.
I think you’re sad and they’ll be glad they made you feel that way.”
Patricia Schroeder, then a congressional Democrat in Colorado, worked with Gary Hart in the presidential election.
In 1987, when Hart was caught having an extramarital affair on a boat called Monkey Business and retired from the race, Schroeder, extremely frustrated, thought she had no reason not to run for president herself.
“It wasn’t a well thought-out decision,” she says, laughing, 30 years later.
“There were already seven other candidates in the race, and the last thing they needed was another one.
Someone referred to the situation as "Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs".
As the campaign was coming to an end, she was behind on the fundraiser and swore she would not enter the race if she failed to raise $2 million.
It was a losing battle.
She found out that some of her supporters who had given the men $1,000, they were only giving her $250.
“Do they think I’m getting cuts?” she asked.
During the speech in which she announced that she would not officially launch a company, she was so affected by emotions – as a result of gratitude for the people who supported her, the frustration caused by the system and the fact that it was so difficult to raise money and target voters instead of delegates, but also the anger caused by gender discrimination – that she lost her voice.
“You would have said I was having a nervous breakdown,” Schroeder recalls of the media’s reactions to her.
“You would have said that one of my sponsors is Kleenex.”
I remember thinking about what they'd write on my gravestone.
“Has he cried?”
How can the trade war between the United States and China be beneficial for Beijing?
The salves that announced the start of the trade war between the United States and China have been deafening, and while there seems to be a long way to go before it ends, the disputes between the two countries could be beneficial for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
U.S. President Donald Trump issued his first warning earlier this year by imposing tariffs on key imports from China, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The biggest escalation came this week with new tariffs affecting $200 billion worth of goods, effectively taxing half of all goods in China that reach the United States.
Beijing has taken revenge each time, most recently imposing a tax of between 5 and 10 percent on $60 billion worth of U.S. goods.
China has warned it will respond to every blow from the United States, and the world’s second-largest economy is unlikely to take a step back in the near future.
For Washington to withdraw, China must agree to its demands, but publicly giving in to the United States would be far too humiliating for Xi Jinping, China’s president.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, U.S. pressures on the trade war could support China positively in the long run, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision taken in Washington or Beijing could lead to an economic collapse in both countries would actually be more dangerous than previously anticipated,” said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher who focuses on Asia at the Center for New American Security, a group of experts.
Syria ready for return of refugees, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild the country ravaged by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
During his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country is improving.
“Today, conditions on the ground are more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists so that things can return to normal.
The existing conditions allow refugees to return voluntarily to the country they were forced to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and livelihoods.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war broke out in 2011.
Six million people who continue to live in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to receive help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or aid from countries sponsored by the insurgency would not be accepted.
