Red tide news: concentrations drop in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Wildlife Protection Commission shows a general drop in red tide concentrations for certain areas of the Gulf of Tampa.
According to the Commission, uneven inflorescence conditions are reported in areas in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – suggesting declining concentrations.
This red tide inflorescence extends over a coastal area of about 210 km from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
The spots can be found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
Red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
The average concentrations found in Pinellas County or its waters were reported last week, as well as low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations in Sarasota County or its waters and high to high concentrations in Charlotte County or its waters.
Airway irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No cases of airway irritation have been reported in northwest Florida in the past week.
